content:
Every Sunday, de boys lime by de road and assess de week. This is what dey seh.
FIRST THING FIRST: HAPPY EASTER
Doodoo seh happy Easter to everybody. Banna seh he ain&rsquo;t eat so much since Christmas and he regretting it already. Fisherman seh he went to early mass, flew a kite with he nephew, and now he sitting down with a plate of cook-up that could feed a small regiment. We taking that as a positive report.
DE PILOT IN DE BUSH
Everybody worried about the ASL pilot. Doodoo seh the GDF boys climbing steep mountain and thick jungle in the hot sun and they nearly reach. Banna seh if that was him in that plane he would&rsquo;ve had a heart attack before the crash. Fisherman seh stop making joke — a man life in the balance and the soldiers doing something hard. We agree. We praying for Captain Castello and we praying for the rescue team too. Good people on both sides of that search.
DE WALES CONTRACT STORY
Kaieteur drop something big this week about the Wales gas project — secret contracts, Guyana already paying Exxon through cost recovery, a take-or-pay agreement for 375 billion cubic feet of gas, and Lindsayca trying to squeeze out another US$250 million on top of the US$82 million they already collect.
Doodoo seh: &ldquo;So when dey tell we the gas was free, the gas wasn&rsquo;t free?&rdquo;
Banna seh: &ldquo;The gas was free like how a credit card is free.&rdquo;
Fisherman seh: &ldquo;Who sign these contracts? Name them.&rdquo;
Nobody could name them. That is the whole problem.
DE NATIONAL CLEANUP
De government held a big national cleanup exercise Saturday. Joint Services, civilians, everybody pick up garbage all over the country.
Banna seh: &ldquo;How long before it dirty again?&rdquo;
Doodoo seh: &ldquo;By Tuesday.&rdquo;
Fisherman seh: &ldquo;That ain&rsquo;t the point. The point is the habit.&rdquo;
Banna seh: &ldquo;Tuesday.&rdquo;
We going with Tuesday.
BARTICA GETTING A HOSPITAL
New hospital breaking ground in Bartica. Twenty-four months to build.
Fisherman seh: &ldquo;Why Berbice people always have to wait the longest for everything? Oil pulling out from right next to them and the hospital just now breaking ground.&rdquo;
Doodoo seh: &ldquo;At least it breaking ground.&rdquo;
Fisherman seh: &ldquo;I want it to break ground in 2022 when they first announce it.&rdquo;
Banna seh: &ldquo;Berbice strong. Berbice accustom waiting.&rdquo;
Fisherman seh: &ldquo;That is not a compliment.&rdquo;
DE OPPOSITION DRAMA
Azruddin Mohamed fire the PNCR woman as Chief Scrutineer. Aubrey Norton talking about don&rsquo;t import crime. The whole opposition bench looking like a group project where everybody disagree on the topic.
Doodoo seh: &ldquo;They fighting each other and they supposed to be fighting the government.&rdquo;
Banna seh: &ldquo;Is good strategy. Keep the government confused about which direction the attack coming from.&rdquo;
Fisherman seh: &ldquo;Banna, that is not strategy. That is chaos.&rdquo;
Banna seh: &ldquo;Confused chaos.&rdquo;
DE SWADISH FOOD FESTIVAL
Multiple international cuisines. Local favourites. Georgetown this weekend.
Fisherman went. He said the curry was adequate. Coming from Fisherman, adequate is high praise. He ate three plates.
FINAL WORD
Doodoo seh: &ldquo;This was a hard week. Plane down, gas contract scandal, cleanup that go dirty by Tuesday. But Harpy Eagles playing today in Antigua. So something to watch.&rdquo;
Banna seh: &ldquo;And Captain Thunderface fly the highest kite on the seawall before he escape.&rdquo;
Fisherman seh: &ldquo;What?&rdquo;
Banna seh: &ldquo;Nothing. Easter thing.&rdquo;
De Boys Seh is a satirical Sunday commentary in Guyanese dialect. De boys are fictional. De opinions are real.

A Speedeet &amp; Wilar Story
Wilar found out about the talent show the same way he found out about most of Speedeet&rsquo;s plans — after it was too late to stop them.
&ldquo;I signed us up,&rdquo; Speedeet said, appearing at the gate on a Tuesday morning with the expression of someone delivering excellent news.
Wilar looked up from his book. &ldquo;Signed us up for what?&rdquo;
&ldquo;De school talent show. End of next week. We going to juggle.&rdquo;
There was a silence.
&ldquo;Speedeet,&rdquo; Wilar said carefully. &ldquo;Can you juggle?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Not yet.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Can I juggle?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Also not yet. But we have a whole week.&rdquo;
Wilar closed his book. This was serious enough to put the book down for. &ldquo;What made you think juggling was a good idea?&rdquo;
&ldquo;I saw a video. De man make it look easy.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Videos always make things look easy. That is the entire purpose of videos.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Wilar. It&rsquo;s THREE balls. We&rsquo;re not stupid.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I am not worried about whether we are stupid. I am worried about whether we can juggle.&rdquo;
Speedeet pulled two oranges and a mango out of his school bag. &ldquo;I borrowed these from my mother kitchen. We start practising now.&rdquo;
Wilar looked at the fruit. He looked at Speedeet. He picked up his book again. &ldquo;I am not responsible for what happens to those oranges.&rdquo;
Day one was bad.
Speedeet threw all three pieces of fruit in the air at the same time, which is not juggling — it is just throwing things. The mango hit the fence. One orange rolled under the step. The other orange hit Wilar on the shoe.
&ldquo;That&rsquo;s not juggling,&rdquo; Wilar said without looking up from his book.
&ldquo;I&rsquo;m warming up.&rdquo;
&ldquo;You&rsquo;re throwing fruit at me.&rdquo;
&ldquo;ONE orange. On the shoe. Barely.&rdquo;
Wilar looked at the orange on the ground. He picked it up. He watched a YouTube video on his phone for four minutes. Then he stood up and began tossing one orange from hand to hand in a clean arc.
&ldquo;You have to start with one,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Then two. Then three.&rdquo;
Speedeet stared at him. &ldquo;You could&rsquo;ve told me that before I threw the mango at de fence.&rdquo;
&ldquo;You didn&rsquo;t ask.&rdquo;
By Thursday, Wilar could do two. Clean, steady, back and forth, both oranges making a smooth figure-eight in the air.
Speedeet could do two on good throws and zero on bad ones, which averaged out to approximately one, depending on the wind.
&ldquo;De show is in eight days,&rdquo; Speedeet said.
&ldquo;I know,&rdquo; said Wilar.
&ldquo;We need three.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I know.&rdquo;
&ldquo;What&rsquo;s the plan?&rdquo;
Wilar considered. &ldquo;The plan is that I do the juggling and you do something else.&rdquo;
Speedeet looked deeply offended. &ldquo;This was MY idea.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Yes. And your ideas are usually better in conception than execution. You had the idea. I&rsquo;m handling the execution.&rdquo;
&ldquo;What am I going to do while you juggle?&rdquo;
&ldquo;You can be the announcer. You&rsquo;re good at talking.&rdquo;
Speedeet thought about this. &ldquo;I DO have a good announcer voice.&rdquo;
&ldquo;You have an extremely loud voice, which is adjacent.&rdquo;
The night of the talent show, the school hall was packed — parents, siblings, teachers, the principal in the front row with her arms folded the way she always sat when she was hoping nothing would go wrong.
Three acts went before them. A girl sang a song very beautifully. Two boys did a comedy skit that was funnier in rehearsal. A younger girl recited a poem and forgot the last verse but nobody minded.
Then it was their turn.
Speedeet walked to the microphone with enormous confidence.
&ldquo;Good evening,&rdquo; he said, in his best announcer voice — which was, in fact, quite good. &ldquo;Tonight, you will witness something extraordinary. Something that required days of preparation, sacrifice, and the destruction of at least two oranges. Ladies and gentlemen, I present to you: THE AMAZING WILAR.&rdquo;
Wilar walked out from the side with three oranges and stood in the centre of the stage.
He threw the first orange up. Then the second. Then the third.
And he juggled.
Not for a long time — maybe twelve seconds. But clean, smooth, all three oranges in the air in a proper pattern, the way it was supposed to look.
The audience applauded. The principal unfolded her arms.
Wilar caught all three oranges and took a small bow.
Speedeet at the microphone said: &ldquo;He learned that in ONE week. Thank you very much, Georgetown!&rdquo;
Nobody had called it Georgetown. It was a school hall. But people laughed, and the clapping went on a little longer.
Afterward, Wilar&rsquo;s mother said she was proud. Speedeet&rsquo;s mother said she wanted her oranges back. The principal said it was &ldquo;unexpectedly professional.&rdquo;
Walking home, Speedeet said: &ldquo;See? I told you juggling was a good idea.&rdquo;
Wilar said: &ldquo;You threw a mango at a fence on day one.&rdquo;
&ldquo;But it ENDED well.&rdquo;
Wilar thought about this for half a block. &ldquo;It did end well,&rdquo; he admitted.
&ldquo;Same time next talent show?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Absolutely not.&rdquo;
But Speedeet was already thinking about what they could do next time. Wilar could tell. He had the look.
Speedeet &amp; Wilar is a Guyanese children&rsquo;s story series. New adventures every Sunday.

Back-a-Truck: the things Guyanese people actually say. Overheard, reported, and presented without further comment. Every Saturday.
AT STABROEK MARKET, TUESDAY MORNING
&ldquo;De cash grant reach?&rdquo; &ldquo;Not yet.&rdquo; &ldquo;Dey say Region 9 getting it now.&rdquo; &ldquo;I ain&rsquo;t in Region 9.&rdquo; &ldquo;Well.&rdquo; &ldquo;Well.&rdquo;
EAST BANK, MORNING TRAFFIC, WEDNESDAY
&ldquo;Move de car nah man!&rdquo; &ldquo;Where I moving it to?!&rdquo; &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know — ANYWHERE.&rdquo; &ldquo;Is one lane! Where you want me go — de canal?!&rdquo; &ldquo;At this point, yes!&rdquo;
OUTSIDE A GOVERNMENT OFFICE, THURSDAY
&ldquo;Dey say de registry tracking all yuh tickets now.&rdquo; &ldquo;What registry?&rdquo; &ldquo;Digital one. For drivers.&rdquo; &ldquo;Tracking dem from when?&rdquo; &ldquo;Now on.&rdquo; &ldquo;Only from now on?&rdquo; &ldquo;I think so.&rdquo; &ldquo;Okay so everything I do before today don&rsquo;t count?&rdquo; &quot;&hellip;I don&rsquo;t think dat&rsquo;s how it work.&quot; &ldquo;Worth a try.&rdquo;
SEAWALL, EASTER MONDAY
&ldquo;Yuh kite gone.&rdquo; &ldquo;I know it gone.&rdquo; &ldquo;It gone far.&rdquo; &ldquo;I said I know.&rdquo; &ldquo;Probably Suriname by now.&rdquo; &quot;&hellip;&quot; &ldquo;You want some of my roti while you processing?&rdquo; &quot;&hellip;Yes please.&quot;
KITTY ROUNDABOUT, ANY DAY
&ldquo;WHO GIVE YOU YOUR LICENCE?!&rdquo; [silence] &ldquo;WHO TEACH YOU TO DRIVE?!&rdquo; [silence] &ldquo;TALK NAH!&rdquo; [window rolls up]
CHINESE SHOP, PIKE STREET, SATURDAY
&ldquo;String?&rdquo; &ldquo;Aisle two.&rdquo; &ldquo;De strong kind.&rdquo; &ldquo;Also aisle two.&rdquo; &ldquo;De really strong kind. Not de kind dat does cut.&rdquo; &quot;&hellip;How much yuh need?&quot; &ldquo;Enough for a kite. Big one.&rdquo; &ldquo;Last week somebody else buy de same thing.&rdquo; &ldquo;Dat was us.&rdquo; &ldquo;Ah.&rdquo; &ldquo;We learning.&rdquo;
WHATSAPP GROUP &lsquo;PIKE STREET FAMILIES 🏠&rsquo;
Granny Doris: Has anyone seen my bamboo? Some pieces cut from de back. [Read by 14] [No reply for 2 hours] Speedeet: Granny I can explain Granny Doris: I already know. Granny Doris: How de kite fly? Speedeet: Good! Until de string cut. Granny Doris: Next time use de string in de green box not de shed. Granny Doris: And ask first. Speedeet: Yes Granny. Granny Doris: Good boy.
LINDEN HIGHWAY, THURSDAY
&ldquo;You hear dey anniversary of de Ronaldo Peters killing?&rdquo; &ldquo;Yeah. One year.&rdquo; &ldquo;Justice still ain&rsquo;t come.&rdquo; &ldquo;No.&rdquo; &quot;&hellip;&quot; &ldquo;No.&rdquo;
END OF DE WEEK OBSERVATION, FRIDAY EVENING, STABROEK
&ldquo;So Guyana get US$761 million in oil for de quarter.&rdquo; &ldquo;Yeah.&rdquo; &ldquo;And de road still like dat.&rdquo; &ldquo;Yeah.&rdquo; &ldquo;And de light still out on my street.&rdquo; &ldquo;Yeah.&rdquo; &ldquo;But de FPSO producing fine.&rdquo; &ldquo;Yeah.&rdquo; &ldquo;Okay.&rdquo; &ldquo;Okay.&rdquo;
Back-a-Truck publishes every Saturday. Everything overheard is fictional or composite. The Guyana Daily Brief does not identify real individuals in satirical content.

Speedeet and Wilar — two boys from Pike Street, Kitty, Georgetown. Every Sunday.
De argument start before dey even reach de seawall.
&ldquo;A kite need a tail,&rdquo; Wilar say. He was carrying de bamboo frame, holding it careful like it was something important. Which it was. Dey had spend two hours building it.
&ldquo;A kite don&rsquo;t need a tail,&rdquo; Speedeet say. He was carrying de string and de extra plastic bag material. &ldquo;A tail is just showing off.&rdquo;
&ldquo;A tail give it stability.&rdquo;
&ldquo;A tail drag it down.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Speedeet. I read about dis.&rdquo;
&ldquo;You read about everything and still can&rsquo;t swim.&rdquo;
Wilar get quiet because dat was true and also not relevant but hard to argue with.
De seawall on Easter Monday was de most serious kite-flying event in de whole Guyanese calendar and everybody on Pike Street knew it. By ten o&rsquo;clock de wall was full — families spreading out along de concrete, coolers and snacks and children running, and above dem a whole sky of kites. Store-bought ones with proper tails and painted designs. Home-made ones like Speedeet and Wilar&rsquo;s, identifiable by their irregular shape and de general air of hope over engineering.
Dey find a good spot near de middle section, away from de family with de very large cooler who looked like dey planned to be there all day and required significant personal space.
&ldquo;You hold de kite,&rdquo; Speedeet say. &ldquo;I hold de string. When I say run, you run.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Why I running? You de one with de string.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Because somebody have to launch it into de wind.&rdquo;
&ldquo;You launch it into de wind.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Wilar.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Speedeet.&rdquo;
Dey look at each other. Wilar had paid for de plastic bag material — forty dollars at de Chinese shop. Speedeet had borrowed de bamboo from his granny yard without fully asking. Dey was equally invested.
&ldquo;We go do it together,&rdquo; Wilar say. &ldquo;I hold de kite up, you run backward with de string.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Run backward?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Into de wind.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Wilar if I run backward I going to hit somebody.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Run backward carefully.&rdquo;
De first attempt: Speedeet run backward carefully. He hit somebody. Not hard — just a brush against a woman who was walking with a roti in her hand. De roti survive. De woman give dem de look. Every Guyanese child know de look. It carry more information than most conversations.
&ldquo;Sorry, Auntie,&rdquo; dem say together.
De kite, meanwhile, had gone up approximately three feet and then turn sideways and land on de seawall.
De second attempt work.
Wilar hold de kite up high. Speedeet back up into a clear space, let out string, felt de pull as de wind catch it, and de kite climb. Six feet. Ten. Twenty. De plastic bag material crinkle and pull, de bamboo frame hold, and de kite was actually flying — actually up there above de other kites, catching a higher wind.
&ldquo;Don&rsquo;t let go,&rdquo; Wilar say. He was watching from below, shading his eyes.
&ldquo;I not letting go.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Let out more string.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I letting out string.&rdquo;
Thirty feet. Forty. De whole ball of string nearly out now, and de kite was pulling strong, straining against Speedeet hand. He could feel it in his shoulder.
&ldquo;Tie it,&rdquo; Wilar say.
&ldquo;To what?&rdquo;
&ldquo;Your wrist.&rdquo;
Speedeet look at his wrist. He look at de kite. He think about de physics of this. He tie it to his wrist anyway because Wilar had paid forty dollars and it seemed right.
De string was old. Dey had find it in Speedeet granny shed. It was good string once. It had seen better days and also better tensions.
It cut.
Just so. Clean.
De kite climb. Up past de other kites. Up above de coconut trees. Up into a wind that was going northwest, away from de seawall, away from Kitty, away from Georgetown.
Dey watch it.
It become a dot.
Den de dot become nothing.
&ldquo;Speedeet.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I know.&rdquo;
&ldquo;It gone.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I was holding de string, Wilar. I know it gone.&rdquo;
Dey stand there for a while. De woman with de roti walk past again going de other direction. She look at dem. She look at de sky where de kite used to be. She shake her head like dis was exactly what she expected from boys who run backward into people.
&ldquo;You think it land in Suriname?&rdquo; Wilar ask.
&ldquo;Probably.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Dey going to wonder what is dis.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Dey going to know is Guyanese. Easter kite reach Suriname every year.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Is a tradition,&rdquo; Wilar agreed.
Dey went back to de Chinese shop. Wilar bought new string — proper string, from de big roll, not whatever was in Speedeet granny shed. De woman at de counter look at dem like she remember dem from earlier, which she probably did.
Dey went back to de seawall.
Dey build a second kite from de spare bamboo and de extra bag material Speedeet had carried.
Dis one had a tail. Speedeet put it on himself without saying anything about it.
Wilar notice but also say nothing.
De kite fly until four o&rsquo;clock when dey had to go home for dinner. It was still in de sky when dey leave. Dat was de best kind of ending.
Speedeet &amp; Wilar publishes every Sunday. This story is fiction set in Georgetown, Guyana. The kite is based on real events that happen every Easter Monday on the seawall. The roti survived.

Speedeet &amp; Wilar: two boys, one friendship, Pike Street, Georgetown. Every Sunday.
De kite string cut at exactly de wrong moment.
Speedeet had been holding it for forty-five minutes. His hand was cramping. De kite — a big diamond-shape one he and Wilar had built from bamboo and plastic bag material de night before — was flying good. Real good. Better than either of dem had expected.
Den de string cut.
Just so.
De kite climb up, up, up, above de seawall, above de coconut trees, above de lampposts, going northwest toward somewhere that was not Georgetown anymore.
&ldquo;Speedeet.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I see it.&rdquo;
&ldquo;It gone.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I know it gone, Wilar. I was holding de string.&rdquo;
Dem two stand on de seawall and watch de kite until it was a dot. Den dey watch de dot. Den de dot was gone and dey was just watching sky.
It had been Wilar idea to build de kite. Easter Monday on de seawall was de most serious kite-flying day in de whole Guyanese calendar and Wilar had a vision. He drew it on a piece of paper. He showed Speedeet. Speedeet looked at it and said it look like a diagram from a science textbook.
&ldquo;It&rsquo;s aerodynamic,&rdquo; Wilar said.
&ldquo;It&rsquo;s a bag on some stick,&rdquo; Speedeet said.
&ldquo;Aerodynamically,&rdquo; Wilar said, &ldquo;a bag on some stick.&rdquo;
Dem get de bamboo from Speedeet grandmother yard where she had a small stand of it near de back fence. She watch dem cut it and did not say anything because she know that Easter kites was a sacred thing and she was not de type of grandmother to stand between children and sacred things.
De plastic bag was from de Chinese shop on de corner. Wilar paid for it with his pocket money. He held it like it was significant.
De seawall on Easter Monday was full. Every family in Kitty seemed to be there. Kites of every size and shape and colour was in de air. Some was fancy store-bought ones with tails and designs. Some was clearly home projects like Speedeet and Wilar&rsquo;s, identifiable by their irregular shapes and the general air of optimism over engineering.
Dem find a spot near de middle section. Wilar held de kite. Speedeet held de string. De plan was: Wilar run, Speedeet let out string, de kite go up, dem both celebrate.
De execution was:
Wilar run.
Speedeet let out string.
De kite go up approximately two feet and then turn sideways and aim itself directly at a woman eating a roti who had to dodge fast.
&ldquo;Sorry, Auntie,&rdquo; dem say together.
De auntie give dem de look. Dem know de look. Every Guyanese child know de look.
Dey try again.
Second attempt: de kite went up. Actually up. Six feet. Eight feet. Speedeet let out more string. Wilar was cheering.
Ten feet.
Fifteen.
Twenty.
&ldquo;It flying, Speedeet!&rdquo;
&ldquo;I know man, I doing it!&rdquo;
Thirty feet, forty, de kite was above de other kites now, catching a wind that was coming off de sea, pulling strong against Speedeet hand. He let out more string. His whole ball of string was almost out.
&ldquo;Tie it to something,&rdquo; Wilar say.
&ldquo;To what?&rdquo;
&ldquo;To your wrist.&rdquo;
Speedeet look at de string. He look at de kite. He look at de sky above de kite.
&ldquo;Wilar if dis kite strong enough to pull de string, it strong enough to pull my arm.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Don&rsquo;t be dramatic.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I am being exact.&rdquo;
He tied it to his wrist anyway. Because Wilar had paid for de bag with his pocket money and it seemed right.
De wind had other plans.
De string cut — old string, too much tension — and de kite was free in approximately one second.
Dey stand there.
&ldquo;We shoulda buy new string,&rdquo; Wilar say.
&ldquo;We shoulda,&rdquo; Speedeet agree.
&ldquo;You think somebody go find it?&rdquo;
&ldquo;It probably land in Suriname.&rdquo;
&ldquo;They going to wonder who flew a plastic bag to Suriname.&rdquo;
&ldquo;They going to know is Guyanese. Is a Easter tradition.&rdquo;
Wilar was quiet for a moment. Then: &ldquo;Speedeet. You want to go get another bag and try again?&rdquo;
Speedeet look at his cramped hand. He look at de sky where de kite used to be. He look at de seawall full of people flying kites that had not disappeared into other countries.
&ldquo;Yeah,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;But dis time we buying proper string.&rdquo;
Dey went back to de Chinese shop.
De auntie with de roti watch dem go. She shook her head. But she was smiling. Because kites was supposed to fly away on Easter. Everybody know dat. It just usually happened on purpose.
Speedeet &amp; Wilar publishes every Sunday. This story is fiction set in Georgetown, Guyana. Happy Easter.

De boys liming on the corner of Robb and Hincks. What deh say? Well&hellip;
On the tint crackdown:
&ldquo;Bai, deh pull over every man except the one in de blacked-out government SUV. Dat one just drive straight through.&rdquo;
&ldquo;De minister say &lsquo;don&rsquo;t call me.&rsquo; She know exactly who does call.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Listen, meh tint was 24% — one percent too dark. Deh fine meh thirty thousand dollars. Meanwhile de man who thief fourteen million in aircraft parts get bail in four hours.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Thirty thousand for tint. Thirty thousand for illegal mining. This country have one price for everything, man.&rdquo;
On the Nicaraguan engineers and the missing $13 million:
&ldquo;Dem resign Monday. Arrest Tuesday. Bail Tuesday night. Gone Wednesday. Dis is speedrun world record, bai.&rdquo;
&ldquo;A prominent businessman visit the station for thirty minutes and suddenly dem get bail. Who dis businessman? Nobody know. Nobody asking. Interesting.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Thirteen million in aircraft parts. Thirteen million! And de police say &lsquo;come back tomorrow at three.&rsquo; Come back tomorrow? Bai, dem was packing before they reach home.&rdquo;
&ldquo;De lawyer say in 23 years he never see dis. Twenty-three years. Dat is a man who practice under multiple governments and he NEVER see dis.&rdquo;
On Frederick Pollard coming home from Venezuela:
&ldquo;Seven months in a Venezuelan jail. Seven months! And the GPF go quiet after one press release.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Is de man own family find him. Not de police. Not de government. De family.&rdquo;
&ldquo;His wife travel to Venezuela to bring him back. That woman strong, bai. Real strong.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Welcome home, Frederick. Sorry it tek seven months and zero official help.&rdquo;
On the U.S. Ambassador defending the Exxon contract:
&ldquo;She say renegotiating is a &lsquo;very bad idea.&rsquo; Of course she say dat — she represent de country dat own Exxon.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Fourteen-point-five percent. That is Guyana share of eleven-point-six billion barrels. Do de math.&rdquo;
&ldquo;GHK Lall compare Exxon to Judas dis morning in de paper. Kaieteur News run it. Boldness.&rdquo;
&ldquo;De Ambassador say &lsquo;just look around when I travel the country.&rsquo; Bai, where exactly she travelling? Because Georgetown drain still flood.&rdquo;
On the Alberttown fire:
&ldquo;Forty people on the street. Most of dem Cuban and Dominican. Nowhere to go.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Fifty-seven rooms in dat building. Fifty-seven. That is a small community, not just a building.&rdquo;
&ldquo;DHL staff pulling out documents during the blaze. Priorities, bai. Priorities.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Investigation ongoing. Translation: nobody knows nothing and nobody going to find out nothing.&rdquo;
On the CARIFTA departure:
&ldquo;Twenty-four athletes leave today for Grenada. Send dem off right, Guyana.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Leon Reddy bowl 4 for 8 yesterday. Four wickets for eight runs. The man is special.&rdquo;
&ldquo;We bring back eight medals from Grenada in 2024. We going back to Grenada. Same track. Same soil. Bring back ten.&rdquo;
De Boys Seh publishes Thursdays and Sundays. All views expressed are from de corner. You know de corner.

A Speedeet &amp; Wilar Story
De rain start Friday night and didn&rsquo;t stop.
By Saturday morning, Pike Street was a river.
Not a deep river. Not a dangerous river. But enough water that Little Sanjay from down de road was already wading through it with he shorts hiked up, looking absolutely delighted.
Speedeet press he face against de window and watch him.
&ldquo;Bai,&rdquo; he say to Wilar, who was sitting at de kitchen table doing absolutely nothing dangerous, &ldquo;you see what I see?&rdquo;
Wilar didn&rsquo;t look up from he book. &ldquo;I see flooding.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I see OPPORTUNITY.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Dat is de same ting right now, Speedeet.&rdquo;
But Speedeet was already pulling on he old sneakers — de ones he mudda always say he should throw away. De ones he keep specifically for situations like dis.
Wilar watch him.
&ldquo;You going outside.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Obviously.&rdquo;
&ldquo;In de flood.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Is not even deep.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Last time you say dat, you was up to yuh waist in de drain by Mr. Persaud shop.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Dat was DIFFERENT. Dat drain had unexpected depth.&rdquo; Speedeet tie he laces. &ldquo;You coming?&rdquo;
Wilar look at de water outside. He look at he book. He look at de water again.
He put down de book.
By de time dem reach Sanjay, three more children from de street had appeared. Nobody plan it. Rain does do dat — pull people outside de same way sunshine does.
Keisha was already organizing.
&ldquo;We doing a race,&rdquo; she announce. &ldquo;Down to de corner and back. Fastest one wins.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Wins what?&rdquo; Speedeet ask.
&ldquo;GLORY,&rdquo; Keisha say, which was always her answer.
Speedeet nod like dis was a perfectly reasonable prize.
Dem race.
Speedeet was fast — faster than everybody on Pike Street, everybody knew dat. But wet road and old sneakers was a different calculation. He hit a slick patch near Miss Doreen gate and his feet went one way and he went another.
He land in de water.
Not hard. Not dangerous.
But SPECTACULARLY.
Water spray six feet in every direction. Sanjay scream. De Marcus twins fell over laughing. Keisha shake she head but she was smiling.
Wilar wade over and look down at him.
Speedeet was lying flat in six inches of floodwater, looking at de grey sky.
&ldquo;You alright?&rdquo; Wilar ask.
&ldquo;I win,&rdquo; Speedeet say.
&ldquo;You did not win. Keisha win.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I win de SPLASH competition.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Dat was not a competition.&rdquo;
&ldquo;It is now.&rdquo;
Later, sitting on de front step in wet clothes while de rain tapered off, Wilar said: &ldquo;Next time de government fix de drains properly, you go have less splashing opportunity.&rdquo;
&ldquo;Den I go appreciate it while I have it,&rdquo; Speedeet said.
Wilar think about dis.
&ldquo;Dat is actually a reasonable philosophy.&rdquo;
&ldquo;I have dem sometimes.&rdquo;
De sun try to come out. Not all de way. Just enough to remind everybody it still exist.
Pike Street start to drain.
It always do.
&mdash; De End &mdash;
